**#** Is a special character and needs to be [encoded][1]. Your file name also includes **&amp;** which immediately stands out as a special character.

A fully safe and encoded version would look like

    &lt;video id=&quot;video&quot; defaultMuted autoplay playsinline controls&gt;
      &lt;source src=&quot;/media/movie/Crash%2C%28%29%3C%3E%7B%7D%40%26%2A%26%28_%29%20Course%20%2315%0A.mp4&quot; type=&quot;video/mp4&quot;&gt;
       Your browser does not support the video tag.
    &lt;/video&gt;

In general you should only use alpha numeric characters with the addition of underscores (_) or hyphens (-) in file names and links. This will ensure maximum compatability across file systems and avoid the need for URL Encoding. 

So yes it&#39;s possible, but not advisable. There are literally thousands of ways to keep the filename meaningful without using reserved characters.


  [1]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Glossary/percent-encoding

